Subject: [PATCH 2/3] =?UTF-8?q?phase=201:=20sh=20=E2=80=94=20drop=20unused?=
 =?UTF-8?q?=20<ucontext.h>=20for=20Darwin=20build?=
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

fault.c #include <ucontext.h> was unreferenced code — only stack_t and
sigaltstack() are used, both from <signal.h>. Darwin gates <ucontext.h>
behind _XOPEN_SOURCE and marks the ucontext_t routines deprecated, so
including it triggered an #error on this platform.

Dropping the include is future-proof: <signal.h> is guaranteed to
carry stack_t + sigaltstack by POSIX, so this build is unchanged on
Linux/BSD and now compiles cleanly on Darwin without needing to
enable a deprecated feature-test macro.

Build verified: sh runs basic scripts, pipes, param expansion, jobs,
here-docs; jsh symlink works; man page installs. Staged to
/tmp/heirloom-stage/opt/heirloom/{bin,share/man/5man/man1}.
---
 fault.c | 7 ++++++-
 1 file changed, 6 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/fault.c b/fault.c
index b17a6cf..0f1f89f 100644
--- a/fault.c
+++ b/fault.c
@@ -39,7 +39,12 @@
  */
 
 #include	"defs.h"
-#include	<ucontext.h>
+/*
+ * Darwin port: <ucontext.h> was included upstream but only stack_t and
+ * sigaltstack() are referenced; both live in <signal.h> (POSIX). Darwin
+ * gates <ucontext.h> behind _XOPEN_SOURCE and deprecates the routines,
+ * so drop the include to stay POSIX-portable. -- Heirloom Darwin port.
+ */
 #include	<errno.h>
 #include	<string.h>
 
